00:45:59.019 --> 00:46:06.769
And so, for me to work there, to walk around
and see Morley Safer and Bob Simon and all

00:46:06.769 --> 00:46:10.339
these correspondents who I have great respect
for and to learn from their producers and

00:46:10.339 --> 00:46:14.740
being able to learn from them is an extraordinary
thing. And I still think I'm getting better

00:46:14.740 --> 00:46:16.799
at it and need to--.

00:46:16.799 --> 00:46:21.380
I still think I'm learning and that's what
makes it so exciting. But I think it's interesting

00:46:21.380 --> 00:46:28.220
how 60 Minutes has started to try to incorporate
online. I mean, 60 Minutes is, CBS in general

00:46:28.220 --> 00:46:37.480
is a very established, traditional outlet,
company. They're very slow to--. A lot of

00:46:37.480 --> 00:46:41.359
these companies are slow to really adapt and
figure out online components and things.

00:46:41.359 --> 00:46:45.720
60 Minutes has actually done--. They actually
have a full-time correspondent now who's excellent,

00:46:45.720 --> 00:46:52.440
who creates--. There's this thing, 60 Minutes
Overtime, which exists only online. And it's

00:46:52.440 --> 00:46:55.569
all the interesting stuff that never actually
makes it into a 60 Minutes piece.

00:46:55.569 --> 00:47:02.250
It's the back story of how the piece was made.
And for instance, with Eminem, we showed how

00:47:02.250 --> 00:47:06.510
just doing a walk--. On 60 Minutes and a lot
of more traditional outlets, they do these

00:47:06.510 --> 00:47:10.380
walking shots, which are cheesy. It's like
the correspondent and the person walking down

00:47:10.380 --> 00:47:11.380
the street.

00:47:11.380 --> 00:47:15.750
And just in order to shoot this walking shot
with Eminem, it required this huge security

00:47:15.750 --> 00:47:21.599
undertaking 'cause it was at the home where
he grew up. And his whole entourage is there

00:47:21.599 --> 00:47:25.059
and there's elaborate security detail and
they had to rope off the block. So, it was

00:47:25.059 --> 00:47:27.759
all the back story on a lot of this stuff.

00:47:27.759 --> 00:47:34.000
And it's actually the more fun moments which
don't make it, naturally, into a 60 Minutes

00:47:34.000 --> 00:47:39.230
piece, but you get value added if you're interested.
So, I think, for me, it seems like the networks

00:47:39.230 --> 00:47:44.580
right now, that's the use they see of these
in trying to again, build a community and

00:47:44.580 --> 00:47:46.470
build a sense of connection to a show like
that.

00:47:46.470 --> 00:47:47.470
&gt;&gt;MALE AUDIENCE MEMBER #4: Thanks.

00:47:47.470 --> 00:47:48.470
&gt;&gt;STEVE GROVE: Yep.

00:47:48.470 --> 00:47:51.829
&gt;&gt;MALE AUDIENCE MEMBER #5: Hi, Anderson. Thank
you for coming to Google. Back in October,

00:47:51.829 --> 00:47:58.269
I went to this little rally that was down
in D.C. and there was you, not you directly,

00:47:58.269 --> 00:48:02.759
but your clothing was a feature of the rally.
They gave your black t-shirt an award.

00:48:02.759 --> 00:48:03.759
&gt;&gt;ANDERSON COOPER: My black t-shirt, yes.

00:48:03.759 --> 00:48:07.529
&gt;&gt;MALE AUDIENCE MEMBER #5: I was wondering
what you thought about the role that you place

00:48:07.529 --> 00:48:12.369
as a feedback system in in the media with
fear and with the things that they were counting

00:48:12.369 --> 00:48:13.810
on, do you think that the business is legitimate?

00:48:13.810 --> 00:48:17.480
&gt;&gt;ANDERSON COOPER: Yeah John actually asked
me to go to that and I would've like to. I

00:48:17.480 --> 00:48:18.839
actually couldn't 'cause I was working, but--

00:48:18.839 --> 00:48:22.190
&gt;&gt;STEVE GROVE: The rally to restore fear at
the mall, right?

00:48:22.190 --> 00:48:26.490
&gt;&gt;ANDERSON COOPER: Right. Yes, yes, yes. Look,
first of all, I wear a black t-shirt or a

00:48:26.490 --> 00:48:34.400
dark t-shirt because--. The back story is
that there's no real thought to it other than

00:48:34.400 --> 00:48:37.890
you're not able to shower in a lot of places
and you're working in like, hundred degree

00:48:37.890 --> 00:48:38.890
temperatures.

00:48:38.890 --> 00:48:43.450
So, you're sweaty and dirty and rather than
having viewers email me saying, "Why are you

00:48:43.450 --> 00:48:47.241
showing us your sweat stains?" I wear a dark
t-shirt so that nobody sees my sweat stains.

00:48:47.241 --> 00:48:54.220
But it has certainly taken on a life of its
own and I think it's funny. So, I don't think

00:48:54.220 --> 00:49:01.640
I'm in any way trying to put fear into anybody's
heart or into anybody's head.

00:49:01.640 --> 00:49:07.650
If anything, I mean, I think for me the reason
to go down to Haiti and be there after the

00:49:07.650 --> 00:49:11.619
earthquake is not to--. It's not a story that
people are necessarily wanting to watch or

00:49:11.619 --> 00:49:16.140
are going to watch. I was just in Somalia
for a week. That's not a story.

00:49:16.140 --> 00:49:20.579
CNN doesn't send me to Somalia because they
think people are gonna want to watch it, or

00:49:20.579 --> 00:49:23.650
that people are even going to watch it. And
they're not because those are things people

00:49:23.650 --> 00:49:28.529
turn the channels from. But I do believe in
bearing witness to what's happening and I

00:49:28.529 --> 00:49:31.520
do believe in giving a voice to people who
have none.

00:49:31.520 --> 00:49:35.259
And in Haiti, for generations, people have
not had a voice or they had their voice silenced

00:49:35.259 --> 00:49:40.450
or taken away from them. And especially after
an earthquake, where the Haitian government

00:49:40.450 --> 00:49:47.059
is completely unable to even dig people out
of the rubble or even are unwilling to. I

00:49:47.059 --> 00:49:51.510
do think there's value in being there and
trying to show the rest of the world what

00:49:51.510 --> 00:49:53.099
is happening to a group of people.

00:49:53.099 --> 00:49:59.490
So for me, I don't think--. I certainly don't
think consciously, or even unconsciously,

00:49:59.490 --> 00:50:07.800
I'm trying to in any way make people fearful.
I do believe in bearing witness to struggles

00:50:07.800 --> 00:50:12.630
that other people aren't. And I've believed
in that from the first time I went to Burma

00:50:12.630 --> 00:50:14.400
and talked to students.

00:50:14.400 --> 00:50:18.299
It's not a conflict anyone seems to really
care much about, or not a lot people care

00:50:18.299 --> 00:50:22.170
much about. But I think it's valuable to be
there. I think it's valuable to give people

00:50:22.170 --> 00:50:23.170
voice.

00:50:23.170 --> 00:50:24.170
&gt;&gt;STEVE GROVE: Great.

00:50:24.170 --> 00:50:25.170
&gt;&gt;MALE AUDIENCE MEMBER #5: Thank you so much
for explaining.

00:50:25.170 --> 00:50:27.019
&gt;&gt;FEMALE AUDIENCE MEMBER #6: So speaking of
fashion, I wanted to know how your beautiful

00:50:27.019 --> 00:50:33.690
mother was and if you share her love of fashion
and what she thinks of you swimming in these

00:50:33.690 --> 00:50:34.690
shark infested waters.

00:50:34.690 --> 00:50:39.319
&gt;&gt;ANDERSON COOPER: My mom is good. My mom
is Gloria Vanderbilt and she's 87 and she's

00:50:39.319 --> 00:50:45.289
great. She's in really good health. And she--.
I do not share her interest in fashion. I

00:50:45.289 --> 00:50:48.180
could care less about it. It really doesn't
interest me. I hate shopping.

00:50:48.180 --> 00:50:52.049
I always, for some reason, I still think when
I go into a store people think I'm stealing

00:50:52.049 --> 00:50:55.740
something. Does anybody else have this? I'm
convinced the sales people think I'm stealing

00:50:55.740 --> 00:50:59.750
something. And I literally feel like I have
to demonstrate to them like, "I'm looking

00:50:59.750 --> 00:51:00.750
at this shirt now."

00:51:00.750 --> 00:51:01.750
[laughter]

00:51:01.750 --> 00:51:10.109
I don't know why I feel this. I hope to work
this out at my daytime show. She's gotten

00:51:10.109 --> 00:51:15.950
used to me going off and doing weird things.
I mean, I said I left high school early and

00:51:15.950 --> 00:51:17.540
drove across sub-Saharan Africa in a truck.

00:51:17.540 --> 00:51:22.740
And I had been doing survival courses as a
very young kid before that in the wilderness

00:51:22.740 --> 00:51:30.259
for like, months at a time. So, she had gotten
used to this idea and she's really sweet about

00:51:30.259 --> 00:51:36.089
it 'cause I lie to her all the time when I'm
away. I was in Egypt and I was like, "I'm

00:51:36.089 --> 00:51:38.150
just gonna hang out by the pool in the hotel
today."

00:51:38.150 --> 00:51:42.000
And then, half an hour later I'm getting beat
up by thugs. And so--

00:51:42.000 --> 00:51:43.800
&gt;&gt;STEVE GROVE: Does your mom watch YouTube?
'Cause she'll see this.

00:51:43.800 --> 00:51:47.390
&gt;&gt;ANDERSON COOPER: I know. Yes, I know. She
knows about it by now. 'Cause then I'll have

00:51:47.390 --> 00:51:51.180
to call her up and be like, "All right. So
I decided not to hang out by the pool and

00:51:51.180 --> 00:51:56.319
I went outside and these people hit me in
the head. And you're gonna see it on TV, but

00:51:56.319 --> 00:51:57.319
it doesn't look as bad."

00:51:57.319 --> 00:52:00.240
I always it doesn't, it wasn't as bad as it
looks on TV, which is also not true 'cause

00:52:00.240 --> 00:52:01.240
it's usually worse. But.

00:52:01.240 --> 00:52:02.240
[laughter]

00:52:02.240 --> 00:52:03.999
&gt;&gt;STEVE GROVE: You're digging a hole.

00:52:03.999 --> 00:52:09.589
&gt;&gt;ANDERSON COOPER: Yeah, but she's--. What's
remarkable about my mom is that she has never

00:52:09.589 --> 00:52:14.349
asked me not to do something. I mean, from
the time I was very little, even doing very

00:52:14.349 --> 00:52:20.580
extreme things, she was very supportive of
it and if she felt I was really passionate

00:52:20.580 --> 00:52:21.580
about it.

00:52:21.580 --> 00:52:22.580
&gt;&gt;FEMALE AUDIENCE MEMBER #6: Thank you.

00:52:22.580 --> 00:52:23.580
&gt;&gt;STEVE GROVE: Let's go over here.

00:52:23.580 --> 00:52:26.440
&gt;&gt;FEMALE AUDIENCE MEMBER #7: I have a question
about how you put your show together. How

00:52:26.440 --> 00:52:33.190
you decide at what stories to bring because
sometimes it's the more broad political agendas

00:52:33.190 --> 00:52:37.170
and then other times it goes much more into
being almost sensational news.

00:52:37.170 --> 00:52:42.119
So, how do you make these decisions? Or, is
it just you or the guidance at CNN?

00:52:42.119 --> 00:52:46.140
&gt;&gt;ANDERSON COOPER: There's not really any
guidance from CNN. I mean, I generally do

00:52:46.140 --> 00:52:50.349
things which I'm interested in, which I think
other people are gonna be interested in. And

00:52:50.349 --> 00:52:55.049
it's a combination. And every day, we sit
around all day thinking of what are we gonna

00:52:55.049 --> 00:52:56.049
do today.

00:52:56.049 --> 00:53:02.240
And we try to start off the broadcast, if
there's not breaking news, with--. We have

00:53:02.240 --> 00:53:05.799
branded it at keeping it honest, but it basically
is what I think all reporters should be doing,

00:53:05.799 --> 00:53:11.200
which is basically just seeing public statements
that have been made and then holding people

00:53:11.200 --> 00:53:15.480
accountable for those statements if they're
correct or not, like the Obama trip to India

00:53:15.480 --> 00:53:16.480
costs thing.

00:53:16.480 --> 00:53:19.980
So, we usually try to lead off the broadcast
with a keeping them honest report if we don't

00:53:19.980 --> 00:53:26.519
have some breaking news. But something like
Syria is something I'm very passionate about

00:53:26.519 --> 00:53:33.480
and I think is important. And very few people
on television news are covering it on a regular

00:53:33.480 --> 00:53:35.499
sustained basis.

00:53:35.499 --> 00:53:39.750
And I think it's important that it get covered.
I had the idea that if you have thousands

00:53:39.750 --> 00:53:43.910
of people who are standing out for their dignity,
being shot to death in the streets by their

00:53:43.910 --> 00:53:50.920
own government, I think is abhorrent and deserves
coverage. Certainly there's some times there's

00:53:50.920 --> 00:53:56.339
stories that I may not be personally all that
interested in, or that I think are all that

00:53:56.339 --> 00:54:00.799
important in a geopolitical sense, but that
people are just genuinely interested.

00:54:00.799 --> 00:54:06.900
And look at the Casey Anthony trial. That's
a story that people were fascinated with and

00:54:06.900 --> 00:54:10.559
for all the people who say they weren't interested
in it, half of those people were still watching

00:54:10.559 --> 00:54:19.990
it. And you're in a news business and my job
is not to tell people to eat their broccoli

00:54:19.990 --> 00:54:20.990
every single night.

00:54:20.990 --> 00:54:25.309
Sometimes, if someone's interested in a story
and there's a high viewer interest in it,

00:54:25.309 --> 00:54:31.249
I'll do that story if we think we can do it
in an intelligent way. So, we try not to be

00:54:31.249 --> 00:54:37.119
sensationalistic about stuff. And I don't
know if there's something specific that you're

00:54:37.119 --> 00:54:45.319
referencing, but certainly everybody's responsible
just for their own little program and I can't

00:54:45.319 --> 00:54:50.130
take credit or responsibility for what else
is on cable news.

00:54:50.130 --> 00:54:56.970
But on my program, we try very hard not to
focus on stuff that's sensational. And what

00:54:56.970 --> 00:55:01.819
we found, frankly, over the years is that
for a CNN viewer, they're really not interested

00:55:01.819 --> 00:55:06.380
in sensational stories. I mean, if somebody's
really, really interested in crime stories,

00:55:06.380 --> 00:55:08.290
they can go to Nancy Grace on HLN.

00:55:08.290 --> 00:55:13.460
She covers what she covers. Or, they could
go to some of the other shows on HLN or elsewhere.

00:55:13.460 --> 00:55:17.430
Or, if they're interested in celebrity interviews,
they go to Pierce Morgan. People don't really

00:55:17.430 --> 00:55:23.619
come to me for that on CNN. They come now
because of the accountability things and also

00:55:23.619 --> 00:55:24.630
a lot of foreign coverage.

00:55:24.630 --> 00:55:30.509
So, I'm happy that I have that niche and that
viewers are actually coming for that. And

00:55:30.509 --> 00:55:31.589
so, that's what I'm able to do.

00:55:31.589 --> 00:55:32.589
&gt;&gt;FEMALE AUDIENCE MEMBER #7: Thanks.

00:55:32.589 --> 00:55:34.480
&gt;&gt;STEVE GROVE: We have time for one more question
over here.

00:55:34.480 --> 00:55:39.070
&gt;&gt;Male Audience Member #8: Speaking on the
topic of where you think things might be going,

00:55:39.070 --> 00:55:44.819
or how you'd like them to go, but particularly
in the developing world where sometimes you're

00:55:44.819 --> 00:55:49.700
covering the stories, do you think that what
we see with Twitter and YouTube and these

00:55:49.700 --> 00:55:51.329
kind of things is making the kind of impact
it could and the affected populations in these

00:55:51.329 --> 00:55:52.329
areas?

00:55:52.329 --> 00:55:53.330
Are they getting the benefit of increased
coverage,

00:55:53.330 --> 00:55:54.410
&gt;&gt;ANDERSON COOPER: Right.

00:55:54.410 --> 00:55:58.749
&gt;&gt;Male Audience Member #8: or is it more just
to have people watching?

00:55:58.749 --> 00:56:03.670
&gt;&gt;ANDERSON COOPER: I think it's hard to generalize.
I mean, I think it depends on each situation.

00:56:03.670 --> 00:56:08.819
But I think certainly some places in Haiti--.
I mean, in Haiti for instance, in the wake

00:56:08.819 --> 00:56:13.180
of the earthquake there were a lot of folks
online who were obviously very concerned and

00:56:13.180 --> 00:56:15.380
wanted to be involved and were trying to help
spread information.

00:56:15.380 --> 00:56:19.900
Like, "This person is trapped in this building."
And I would get these tweets. I would get

00:56:19.900 --> 00:56:25.779
these emails. I mean, thousands of them every
single day while I was down in Haiti for that

00:56:25.779 --> 00:56:32.230
month. And 99% of them are very well-intentioned.
A lot of them are just this echo chamber of

00:56:32.230 --> 00:56:36.119
somebody else has put this email out there.

00:56:36.119 --> 00:56:39.630
And it's been picked up by ten other concerned
people and then it's been forwarded and it's

00:56:39.630 --> 00:56:44.690
taken on a life of its own. And it grows in
hysteria to the point where you get an email

00:56:44.690 --> 00:56:48.840
from a very serious sounding person who's
saying there are kids who are crushed and

00:56:48.840 --> 00:56:55.829
starving in this orphanage and they're at
28, and they give the address, and you drive

00:56:55.829 --> 00:57:01.239
for half a day to get there only to learn
that actually the kids are fine here.

00:57:01.239 --> 00:57:05.030
It's not a great situation, but they have
enough food for two or three weeks and it's

00:57:05.030 --> 00:57:09.569
not what it was made into. And we've had a
number of those situations where we've actually

00:57:09.569 --> 00:57:17.259
responded to things which came to us with
the best of intentions. So, it can be an issue.

00:57:17.259 --> 00:57:23.910
It can also be somebody trapped underneath
a house can send out an email and their loved

00:57:23.910 --> 00:57:29.450
one can see it and relief can come, help can
come. And that has happened as well. So, it's

00:57:29.450 --> 00:57:34.940
a case by case basis. But I do think overall,
I mean, it’s incredible, positive, that

00:57:34.940 --> 00:57:38.930
I think any way you can engage people, any
way you can get people to focus on--.

00:57:38.930 --> 00:57:44.119
Everyone's so busy and they don't have time
necessarily to even sit and watch a news clip.

00:57:44.119 --> 00:57:49.619
But to read a headline online that maybe spurs
them to do something. Or, there's just extraordinary

00:57:49.619 --> 00:57:54.999
things being done by Google and on Google
and by YouTube, helping people coordinate

00:57:54.999 --> 00:57:59.099
and helping people organize and I mean, I
know people from Google who went down to Haiti

00:57:59.099 --> 00:58:04.349
and I don't know what they were doing, but
something on the computer to help--

00:58:04.349 --> 00:58:05.999
[laughter]

00:58:05.999 --> 00:58:16.430
I'm a total Luddite. I'm there with my quill
pen and I see them with laptops, but to help

00:58:16.430 --> 00:58:22.049
data storage and to help organize what stuff
is coming in and what's going out. I mean,

00:58:22.049 --> 00:58:23.089
that's incredible.

00:58:23.089 --> 00:58:27.880
And it really is revolutionizing the way aid
is delivered. And it can really revolutionize

00:58:27.880 --> 00:58:32.089
things and I think it's incredibly exciting
to see because it really does have an impact

00:58:32.089 --> 00:58:37.150
on the ground. I mean, just one quick example.
I was in Haiti when eight days after the quake,

00:58:37.150 --> 00:58:44.049
a woman, an elderly woman, I think she was
in her 70s was found alive, trapped by a building

00:58:44.049 --> 00:58:45.049
near the Cathedral.

00:58:45.049 --> 00:58:48.319
She had been trapped under the wreckage for
eight days. And it was incredible that she

00:58:48.319 --> 00:58:52.770
was still alive. And she gets pulled out by
some South African and Mexican search and

00:58:52.770 --> 00:58:58.800
rescue people, but they were so excited and
elated that they pulled her out, no one had

00:58:58.800 --> 00:59:01.230
thought of the next step of, "Well, what do
we do with her now?"

00:59:01.230 --> 00:59:07.980
And there were no real--. Her pelvis was crushed,
I think. Part of her leg was crushed. And

00:59:07.980 --> 00:59:13.599
she needed life support and she needed surgery
immediately. And there was no place to take

00:59:13.599 --> 00:59:17.990
her. And they had no knowledge of where there
was a doctor who could actually perform the

00:59:17.990 --> 00:59:19.849
kind of surgery she needed.

00:59:19.849 --> 00:59:26.299
And we ended up, I mean, me, my team of two
other people ended up in this weird position

00:59:26.299 --> 00:59:33.749
where we found ourselves with her in the back
of our truck, on a stretcher, trying to mobilize

00:59:33.749 --> 00:59:38.140
people online and mobilize resources over
the phone that we could bring her to.

00:59:38.140 --> 00:59:45.500
And we ended up getting her on board a US
Coast Guard helicopter that landed on the

00:59:45.500 --> 00:59:49.910
Presidential Palace that had been destroyed.
And my producer is on the front lawn waving

00:59:49.910 --> 00:59:56.670
the chopper in with his BlackBerry light.
And I mean, that shouldn't happen. And so,

00:59:56.670 --> 00:59:59.980
the ability to connect people who are on the
ground, 'cause when you're on the ground you

00:59:59.980 --> 01:00:01.710
have no way of really sharing information.

01:00:01.710 --> 01:00:06.130
And I think that's the next step--the ability
for in real-time, people who are on the ground

01:00:06.130 --> 01:00:10.279
to connect information and connect resources.
That would be an extraordinary step.

01:00:10.279 --> 01:00:12.320
&gt;&gt;STEVE GROVE: Well, Anderson. Thanks for
coming today.

01:00:12.320 --> 01:00:13.320
&gt;&gt;ANDERSON COOPER: Cool. Thank you.

01:00:13.320 --> 01:00:14.320
[applause]

01:00:14.320 --> 01:00:18.549
&gt;&gt;STEVE GROVE: Before we let you go, we want
to give you an essential pair of YouTube tube

01:00:18.549 --> 01:00:19.549
socks.

01:00:19.549 --> 01:00:20.650
&gt;&gt;ANDERSON COOPER: That's fine. That's great.

01:00:20.650 --> 01:00:23.099
&gt;&gt;STEVE GROVE: I'm sure you'll wear them the
next time you're out here.

01:00:23.099 --> 01:00:25.039
&gt;&gt;ANDERSON COOPER: I will. I'll wear them
with my black t-shirt. Thank you.

01:00:25.039 --> 01:00:27.640
